Once I got used to eating within a window, my body eventually capitulated on hunger outside of it. I make sure my meals are as physically big as possible and full of fibre, loads of spinach, mushrooms and broccoli. Shirataki noodles are a constant staple and an excellent low calorie filler. b' '
WRITING.TEXT:
b'I'm afraid I can't see that as a positive:
Corporation produces crap. "Designer sunnies" for example, unrecyclable plastic lenses that cost them 50p to produce and sell for \xc2\xa3400. They spend resources to freight them to an Amazon warehouse. Customer buys them and doesn't like them. Van takes them back to warehouse. Amazon bundles them up into a box of general crap that people didn't want, like or need and sells them again. Van takes them to new customer in assumedly an insane amount of Amazon style packaging. Whereupon the new customer packages them up again, and send them in a van to another customer paying another e-commerce platform 12% for the privilege.

1. That is the most inefficient way of providing a resource to a resource user.
2. The intrinsic value of the resource is in no way reflected in the cost imposed on the user.
3. The environmental aspect of the operation is horrendous.
4. The tabloid media being used to market Amazon selling real world loot boxes to a generation of people trained to think with that mentality through live service video games is disgusting. What's the likelihood of getting a box of goods where the price paid is consistently lower than the combined value of the goods contained? If it's a high likelihood then why wouldn't Amazon just resell the products themselves. They like money.

Sorry to rant. I just hate inefficiency.'

WRITING.TEXT:
b"Pan fried Salmon fillets and prawns with green beans and capers, with a creamy blue cheese and spinach sauce on a bed of edamame and mung bean fettuccine.

Iceland - Salmon Fillet (Frozen), 240g

Asda Smartprice - Frozen Prawns, 100g

Iceland - Freshly Frozen Whole Leaf Spinach, 100g

Iceland - Frozen Green Beans, 80g

Aldi - Capers, 2 tbs

Aldi - Single cream, 99ml

Philadelphia - Philadelphia, 90g

Asda - English Blue Stilton Cheese, 50g

Aldi - Edamame and Mung Bean Fettuccine, 184g (50g dry)

1. Defrost the fish and prawns in advance. I would normally place in a bag in a bowl of lukewarm water for 20 minutes.
2. Fry up the salmon fillets. Place the hob on a medium high heat, put some oil in a plan and place the fillets in skinside first and flip after 4 minutes.
3. Stick the spinach in the microwave until it's cooked. About 3 minutes on high for an 800W microwave.
4. Bang the fettuccine in a pot with some salt and boiling water. Adjust the hob so the water simmers and cook for 5 minutes.
5. Season another pan with garlic or whatever you fancy, medium heat, plop the cooked spinach in there. At this point you should be about ready to flip the fish.
6. Put the green beans in the microwave for 3 minutes on high. Throw in the cheeses and cream on the spinach. Mix it about a bit and cook until the green beans ding in the microwave.
7. Turn the hob off on the fish and the fettuccine and then drain it.
8. Toss the prawns into the sauce. Mix it about a bit more and cook for another minute.
9. Jam it all on a plate and sprinkle the capers on the fish

1379 calories 122g protein 87g fat 19g carbs

Good for if you've had a light lunch or your stupid car has broken down and you've had to start cycling to work and need to up your intake.

Halve everything for a probably more normal sized meal."

WRITING.TEXT: b"Onions and root vegetables are only good in small amounts if you want to keep the carbs down.
